		<header>
			
			<h1>Decision time approaching for West African EPA process </h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 March 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Ghana’s Minister of Trade and Industry, Hannah Tetteh, has stressed that ‘Ghana wants an ECOWAS consensus’ on outstanding contentious issues in the EPA negotiations, but has pointed out that Ghana still had ‘the interim EPA as a fall-back should we not reach a consensus within the stipulated time-frame’ (i.e. before the deadline of 1 January 2014 for signing and ratifying the initialled IEPAs, beyond which the duty-free, tariff-free access granted under EU Council Regulation 1527/(2007) would be withdrawn).</p><p>Ms Tetteh acknowledged that ‘it is true that in signing the full EPA we shall gain in some areas and lose in others, but we need to measure the gains against the losses and decide on what is best for the nation.’ She pointed out that since Ghana exports the same products to the EU as Côte d’Ivoire, ‘should we refuse to sign the EPAs, our exporters will simply move their operations to Côte d’Ivoire’. In this context, press reports note that the EU is Ghana’s main target market for diversifying its non-traditional exports. These include banana exports, which increased by nearly 20% in 2011, and a growing level of pineapple exports.</p><p>In terms of prospects for a regional West African EPA agreement, press analysis highlights Nigerian concerns over the impact of the proposed regional EPA on local industries. This needs to be seen in the light of Nigerian proposals to introduce import bans on rice and wheat, once self-sufficiency targets have been attained in the coming five years (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘Nigeria’s ambitious plans for rice and wheat self-sufficiency to see import bans introduced’, forthcoming).</p><p>Meanwhile, Ghana’s Vice President John Dramani Mahama has called for greater efforts to overcome barriers to trade in West Africa. Speaking at an ECOWAS parliamentary workshop, he was critical of the ‘unofficial check-points and barriers that exist on the highways in ECOWAS member countries’. A survey from the West African trade hub quarterly survey recently showed that for every 100 kms there were an average of 17 unofficial controls, each lasting an average of 55 minutes and requiring ‘an average of US$54 paid as bribes’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Peacefmonline.com</i>, ‘The Economic Partnership Agreements debate’, 27 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://business.peacefmonline.com/economy/201202/97181.php" target="_self">http://business.peacefmonline.com/economy/201202/97181.php</a></p><p><i>Daily Guide</i> (Ghana), ‘Ghana exports 62,000 tonnes bananas’, 6 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.dailyguideghana.com/?p=38481" target="_self">http://www.dailyguideghana.com/?p=38481</a></p><p><i>The Africa Report</i>, ‘ECOWAS lagging behind SADC, EAC, COMESA in integration’, 2 March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/02/ecowas-lagging-behind-sadc-eac-comesa-in-integration/" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/2012/03/02/ecowas-lagging-behind-sadc-eac-comesa-i...</a></p><p><i>Ghanaweb.com</i>, ‘Europe is the key market for banana market growth’, 8 February 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=92636" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=92636</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The failure to get to grips in West Africa with the unofficial non-tariff barriers to trade highlighted by the Ghanaian vice-president makes a significant contribution to the disarticulation of the coastal and hinterland economies of West Africa. The hard reality is that when serving coastal consumers, it is often easier and less expensive to source food and agricultural products from the EU than from neighbouring West African producers. Unless these and other non-tariff obstacles to intra-regional trade can be addressed, and new efficient trading networks established between coastal markets and production zones in the interior (e.g. for beef and dairy products), then the elimination of tariffs and the removal of non-tariff barriers on trade with the EU may serve to further exacerbate the apparent disarticulation of the West African regional economy.</p><p>While this can be seen as undesirable in the long term, in the short term governments in countries such as Ghana may decide to finalise bilateral FTA arrangements with the EU in order to retain markets for both non-traditional exports and the development of value added processing activities within traditional supply chains (e.g. cocoa).</p><p>It remains to be seen, however, to what extent the ongoing negotiation process at the regional level will secure concessions as regards the use of trade policy tools to defend sensitive sectors, in line with existing EU policy practice (e.g. in the poultry sector, where the EU makes used of a sophisticated tariff policy to defend the European poultry sector while responding to evolving consumer demand).</p>
		</div>
		
